or Spurs.</p><p>He is not quite in the same league as either player, but Bale has hit free-kicks like Cristiano Ronaldo and scored solo goals that have been reminiscent of Lionel Messi. The stabbed shot against Swansea at the end of March, struck before Michel Vorm had even had time to think and past the goalkeeper in a flash, could have been included in a Messi showreel.</p><p>It could be argued, though, that Bale packed his finest work into a two-month period and similar accusations will be thrown at Robin van Persie, who has been sluggish since the middle of January. The Dutchman recently went 10 games without a goal for Manchester United and missed crucial chances during the defeat by Real Madrid in the Champions League. But by then his work in the league had been done. Without his 21 goals, such as the<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QyNSBnOerrQ\" title=\"\"> last-minute winner in the Manchester derby in December</a>, United would not be 13 points clear of Manchester City.</p><p>He has benefited, too, from the way that Michael Carrick has pulled the strings in midfield. Having been the object of much scorn for so long, largely because he has been unable to compete with Xavi and Andrés Iniesta in two Champions League finals, people are finally starting to appreciate Carrick's true worth. He remains an 80-1 longshot though, and will not win.</p><p>Brendan Rodgers has repeatedly been making the case for Luis Suárez and if the award is based on consistency rather than trophies, it should go to the Liverpool striker. Unlike Van Persie and Bale he has been imperious throughout, and has scored hat-tricks against Norwich and Wigan. The Uruguayan is not a flat-track bully, though. Despite playing in an inferior team, there have been goals against Arsenal, Chelsea, City, Everton, United and Tottenham. Liverpool might only be seventh, but who knows where they might have been without Suárez who has Stewart Downing for company instead of, say, Mata.</p><p>Bale and Hazard are also on the shortlist for the Young Player of the Year – whether they should feature on both is debatable – and the former is being tipped to win both awards. Christian Benteke would be a better choice. His goals could keep Aston Villa up and there are bigger clubs who are kicking themselves for not spotting him last summer. Romelu Lukaku has also made a strong impression during his loan spell at West Bromwich.</p><p>However there are surely more deserving candidates than Jack Wilshere and Danny Welbeck. The former has not truly caught the imagination, while the latter has only scored twice despite playing up front for the champions-elect. If you could combine Welbeck and Javier Hernández, you would have the perfect forward but that remains a problem for a mad scientist to solve. Southampton's Luke Shaw, Manchester City's Matija Nastasic and Wigan's James McCarthy can all feel aggrieved not to have been shortlisted.</p><p>It's just a bit of fun though, nothing to get too worked up over. Unless you're a goalkeeper or a defender. There isn't a single one on either shortlist.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/pfa-player-year-awards\">PFA Player of the Year awards</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/gareth-bale\">Gareth Bale</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/eden-hazard\">Eden Hazard</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/luis-suarez\">Luis Suárez</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/robin-van-persie\">Robin van Persie</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/jacob-steinberg\">Jacob Steinberg</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http: