t=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/signup/2010/mar/30/1\" title=\"\">Click here to have the Fiver sent to your inbox every weekday at 5pm, or if your usual copy has stopped arriving</a></p><h2>GONG!</h2><p>The Fiver went to an awards night once. It wasn't nominated for anything, per se, even though there was a category for The Least Funny Tea-time Email, and it wasn't invited, per se, but it still went to one. Admittedly it had to wear a cunning disguise – no one recognises the Fiver in a suit, unless it's in court – to sneak past the heavies on the door and it was later chucked out after staging a one-man protest when the gongs were being handed out, but still, what a night 8 November 1997 was! With that in mind, the Fiver understands all too well how Gareth Bale, Michael Carrick, Eden Hazard, Juan Mata, Luis Suárez and Robin van Persie are feeling after they were named on the PFA's shortlist for Player of the Year. Panicked. They've got to get new suits, practise their acceptance speech, unless they're Michael Carrick, and practise their rictus grin/grudging applause combo if they lose, especially if they're Michael Carrick.</p><p></p><p>That's harsh on Carrick, isn't it? He's been excellent. He's not going to win, and nor are Eden Hazard and Juan Mata. It's between Gareth Bale, the star of Gareth Bale and The Hotspurs, Robin van Persie and Luis Suárez. Suárez? Boo! Hiss! However unlike Sports Personality of the Year, the PFA doesn't dish this one out based on who has the best personality, which would see Mata win. It's who's had the best season and, after careful consideration which consisted of closing its eyes and picking a name out of a hat, The Fiver has decided to give Suárez its imaginary vote and Liverpool's manager, Brentan Rodgers, is backing his player too. \"There isn't a club in the country who wouldn't want Suárez in their team. He'd be the favourite for me,\" said Rodgers, somehow resisting the urge to say \"myself\" instead of \"me\".</p><p></p><p>Some have claimed that Suárez's past misdemeanours mean that the quality of his football shouldn't be recognised, which is clearly total pish, and he has been defended by the PFA's head honcho Gordon Taylor. \"Sometimes controversy travels with players,\" said Taylor. \"Sometimes it is in their very nature. Sometimes it is that very intensity that causes a problem also makes sure they win.\" Admittedly that doesn't quite excuse the diving and the eight-match ban for racially abusing Patrice Evra in 2011 but can't we all just get along? This isn't meant to be a popularity contest, although it should be pointed out that Suárez's intensity has only allowed Liverpool to win 13 of their 33 league matches. And when you put it like that, it's a disgrace that nice, useless Fernando Torres hasn't been nominated.</p><p></p><h2>QUOTE OF THE DAY</h2><p>\"He said we should go on holiday, making a gesture with his hand\" – Jorge Pellicier, manager of the Chilean champions Huachipato, is irked by the hitherto little-known go-on-holiday hand gesture of Grêmio head coach Verderlei Luxemburgo after the sides' Copa Libertadores fixture <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/video/2013/apr/19/copa-libertadores-brawl-gremio-huachipato-video\" title=\"\">ended in this right old ruckus</a>.</p><p></p><h2>FIVER LETTERS</h2><p>\"I would like to add a second tier of pedantry to Jamie Milne's letter on a suitable Cardiff mascot today (yesterday's Letters). We don't have native bluebirds (native to the Americas) in the UK, rather blue tits. An ideal mascot for crowd 'banter'\" – James Marsden.</p><p></p><p>\"All the chat about Indonesia and Malaysia in the first two pedantgrams (yesterday's Letters) made me read 'gargantuan error' as 'orangutan error' and assume you'd managed to hire some higher-calibre recruits to the Fiver's writing team to join your infinite number of monkeys. I was disappointed when I realised my mistake, but thought I'd pass it on anyway in case you're looking for tips when you're next hiring\" – Jon Gerrard.</p><p></p><p>\"As I was sat reading yesterday's Fiver over a large plate of nasi goreng in Kuala Lumpur I came across a letter from a Rob Jordan claiming that said dish was Indonesian! Bahasa is spoken in both Malaysia and Indonesia (albeit with differences) but without doubt nasi goreng (meaning fried rice) is Malaysian. Just like Cardiff\" – Chris Prior.</p><p></p><p>\"It was good to see Barry Rogerson go with the tried and tested 'some of my best friends are animals' defence. (Wednesday's Quote Of The Day). Maybe if he'd continued, we'd have learnt that his grandfather was actually a horse, and a big ol' punch in the face is actually a sign of affection in his culture\" – Matt Dony.</p><p></p><p>\"Well considering weight plays such a crucial role in the relativity of stopping distances, it probably does take Big Sam 300 yards to stop. And to be fair to him, he probably does have a bespoke Highway Code to go along with his equatorial waistline, gravitational pull, turning circle of an ocean liner etc. and the like\" – Steven Dunne.</p><p></p><p>\"So I suppose PSG's loss to Evian in the French Cup pours cold water on the idea that they are a team capable of winning major honours?\" – Seamus Scanlon.</p><p></p><p>Send your letters to <a href=\"mailto:the.boss@guardian.co.uk\" title=\"\">the.boss@guardian.co.uk</a>. And if you've nothing better to do you can also <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TheFiver\" title=\"\">tweet the Fiver</a>.</p><p></p><p>• Send your letters to <a href=\"mailto:the.boss@guardian.co.uk\" title=\"\">the.boss@guardian.co.uk</a>. Also, if you've nothing better to do you can also <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TheFiver\" title=\"\">tweet the Fiver</a>. And each day this week we're giving away a <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/You-Are-The-Ref-Football/dp/B00BTGL4BI\" title=\"\">You are the Ref board game</a> for the letter of the day. Today's winner: Matt Dony.</p><p></p><h2>JOIN GUARDIAN SOULMATES</h2><p></p><p>We keep trying to point out the utter futility of advertising an online dating service \"for interesting people\" in the Fiver to the naive folk who run Guardian Soulmates, but they weren't having any of it. <a href=\"http://bit.ly/NFqYtq\" title=\"\">So here you go – sign up here</a> to view profiles of the kind of erudite, sociable and friendly romantics who would never dream of going out with you.</p><p></p><h2>BITS AND BOBS</h2><p>Kick It Out is to launch two apps next season – one for players and one for fans – to make it easier to report r@cist abuse.</p><p></p><p>Gareth Bale, Christian Benteke, Eden Hazard, Romelu Lukaku, Danny Welbeck and Jack Wilshere are on the PFA Young Player of the Year award shortlist, while Gemma Davison, Toni Duggan, Jessica Fishlock, Kim Little, Jordan Nobbs, and Jodie Taylor are shortlisted for the women's prize</p><p></p><p>Sir Alex Ferguson has confirmed that Ashley Young has been ruled out for the rest of the season with ankle knack sustained in United's defeat in the Manchester derby.</p><p></p><p>More Fergie time, on this occasion moving to quash rumours linking Wayne Rooney with PSG.</p><p></p><h2>STILL WANT MORE?</h2><p>\"De Gea came back for more, bristling like a lovable cartoon puppy, the hardest kid in chess club, seeming to grow in conviction with every scragging. If you strike him down, it turns out, he will become more powerful than you can possibly imagine …\" –<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/blog/2013/apr/19/david-de-gea-andy-carroll-manchester-united\" title=\"\"> Barney Ronay on the Manchester United goalkeeper's watershed moment</a>.</p><p></p><p>Like the Police Academy films and Weird Uncle Fiver's last birthday 'party', the 80s should remain a fading bad memory, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/blog/2013/apr/19/football-beware-hooliganism\" title=\"\">writes David Lacey</a></p><p></p><p>From Fuller's funk to a shirtless substitution, Jacob Steinberg selects half a dozen comedy red cards in <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/blog/2013/apr/19/joy-of-six-comedy-red-cards\" title=\"\">this week's Joy of Six</a></p><p></p><p>Kidderminster Harriers are on the verge of completing the greatest turnaround since Total Eclipse of the Heart, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/blog/2013/apr/19/kidderminster-harriers-blue-square-premier\" title=\"\">writes Stuart James</a></p><p></p><p>South American football isn't all <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/video/2013/apr/19/brazilian-neymar-cartoon-character-video\" title=\"\">cartoons</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/video/2013/apr/19/copa-libertadores-brawl-gremio-huachipato-video\" title=\"\">violence</a> – Jack Lang of the Guardian Sport Network <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/snap-kaka-pop-blog/2013/apr/19/brazilian-football-sao-paulo-copa-libertadores\" title=\"\">fills you in on the week in Brazil</a></p><p></p><p></p><h2>SIGN UP TO THE FIVER</h2><p></p><p>Want your very own copy of our free tea-timely(ish) email sent direct to your inbox? Has your regular copy stopped arriving? <a href=\"http://bit.ly/9gwaJ4\" title=\"\">Click here to sign up.</a></p><p></p><h2>CRUMB THAT GROUND BALL</h2><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/jacob-steinberg\">Jacob Steinberg</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://guardian.co.uk.feedsportal.com/c/34708/f/639039/s/2aec2445/mf.gif' border='0'/><div class='mf-viral'><table border='0'><tr><td valign='middle'><a href=\"http://share.fee