aims from former owner Craig Whyte<br />• Green maintains he has done nothing wrong</p><p>Charles Green has stepped down from his position as chief executive at Rangers with immediate effect, the Third Division club have told the Stock Exchange.</p><p>The Rangers board announced last week that they will commission an independent investigation into Green's and Imran Ahmad's management of the club and recent allegations in the media.</p><p>The investigation was launched after the club's directors – including the former manager Walter Smith – met at Murray Park last weekend.</p><p>The summit followed claims made by the former owner Craig Whyte of his involvement with Green and the commercial director Ahmad when their consortium completed the purchase of Rangers' business and assets last summer.</p><p>Green – who recently apologised after being charged by the Scottish Football Association for allegedly using \"racist and offensive language\" – rejected the allegations by Whyte, who was in charge when the club plunged into administration and subsequently liquidation. It is understood that Green feels the decision to step down as chief executive is in the best interests of the club, following recent adverse publicity, but that he remains adamant he has done nothing wrong. He is the club's largest single shareholder.</p><p>The Rangers manager, Ally McCoist, speaking at his pre-match press conference on Friday, ahead of Saturday's visit of Peterhead, was asked when he was last in contact with Green.</p><p>McCoist said: \"I haven't spoken to him verbally since last weekend but I've been in contact via emails and a couple of texts. As far as I know, he's in France having a well-earned break.</p><p>\"I don't have any doubt we will meet up when he comes back. We've got a lot to discuss in taking the club forward in terms of players and pre-season training and all that stuff.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a h